    <!-- SECTION: WHO SHOULD AVOID -->
    <h2>Who Should Avoid Creatine?</h2>

    <p>Despite the strong safety profile, certain women should consult a healthcare provider before starting creatine or avoid it entirely.</p>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Consult a healthcare provider before starting creatine if you:</strong></p>
      <ul style="margin:12px 0 0 0;padding-left:20px;">
        <li>Have any pre-existing kidney disease, history of kidney stones, or are taking nephrotoxic medications</li>
        <li>Have liver disease or significantly elevated liver enzymes</li>
        <li>Are pregnant or breastfeeding (see our guide on <a href="/blog/creatine-while-pregnant/">creatine while pregnant</a>)</li>
        <li>Are taking prescription medications, especially diuretics, NSAIDs, or cyclosporine</li>
        <li>Have a history of bipolar disorder (creatine may interact with mood stabilization)</li>
        <li>Are under 18 years old (the safety database in this population is limited)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>For most healthy adult women, none of these contraindications apply, and creatine remains one of the safest supplement choices available. When in doubt, a brief conversation with your primary care physician resolves the question quickly.</p>

