      <h3>Our Verdict: Creatine Is Safer Than Most Common Supplements</h3>
      <p><strong>For healthy adult women, creatine carries one of the strongest safety profiles in nutritional science.</strong> Five-year studies, hundreds of trials, and decades of athletic use have not identified the dramatic side effects that internet folklore continues to claim. The real, documented effects — mild water weight gain, occasional GI discomfort, rare cramping — are mild, reversible, and avoidable with sensible practices.</p>
      <p>The myths — bulky muscles, hair loss, hormonal disruption, kidney damage — do not survive scrutiny against the broader evidence base. Women considering creatine should weigh these mild, well-characterized effects against the substantial benefits documented for strength, cognition, bone density, mood, and lean mass preservation.</p>
      <p>If you have a pre-existing condition or take prescription medications, consult your healthcare provider. For everyone else, the side effect picture is reassuringly clean.</p>
